            "title": "Johnson & Johnson Gets FDA Approval for Blood Cancer Treatment",
            "description": "<div class=\"txt-s4 article-text\"><p>\n  By Kelly Cloonan </p><br/><p>\n  Johnson &amp; Johnson received approval from the Food and Drug Administration for a treatment for certain patients with multiple myeloma, an incurable form of blood cancer. </p><!-- Article --><p>\n\n  The healthcare conglomerate said Tuesday the treatment, darzalex faspro in combination with bortezomib, lenalidomide and dexamethasone, was approved for adult patients with newly diagnosed multiple myeloma who are ineligible for autologous stem cell transplant. </p><p>\n\n  The treatment was previously approved for such patients who are eligible for autologous stem cell transplant, J&amp;J said. </p><p>\n\n  In a recent Phase 3 study, the drug increased the depth and durability of patient responses and reduced the risk of disease progression or death, said Saad Usmani, the study's principal investigator and chief of the myeloma service at Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center. </p><p>\n\n  Multiple myeloma is the second-most common blood cancer worldwide. It is estimated that more than 36,000 people will be diagnosed with multiple myeloma in the U.S. this year, and more than 12,000 will die from the disease, J&amp;J said. </p><br/><p>\n  Write to Kelly Cloonan at kelly.cloonan@wsj.com </p><br/><p>\n  (END) Dow Jones Newswires</p><p>\n\n  01-27-26 1642ET</p></div>",
